  "prompt": "How do you get over someone you never were in a relationship with?",
  "response": "Getting over someone you were never in a relationship with can be just as challenging as moving on from a past relationship because unrequited feelings or unmet expectations can leave a strong emotional impact. Here are some steps to help you heal and move forward:\n\n### 1. **Acknowledge Your Feelings**\n   - Accept that your emotions are valid, even if the relationship never existed. It's okay to feel hurt, disappointed, or confused.\n   - Journaling or talking to a trusted friend can help you process your emotions.\n\n### 2. **Distance Yourself**\n   - Limit contact with the person if possible, especially in the early stages of healing. This can help reduce triggers and give you space to focus on yourself.\n   - Unfollow or mute them on social media to avoid reminders of their presence.\n\n### 3. **Focus on Reality, Not Fantasy**\n   - Remind yourself that the relationship you envisioned was based on potential, not reality. It\u2019s easy to idealize someone when you\u2019re infatuated, but recognize that your feelings may have been tied to an imagined version of them.\n   - Write a list of reasons why it might not have worked out or why they weren\u2019t the right person for you.\n\n### 4. **Redirect Your Energy**\n   - Invest in your personal growth and hobbies. Pick up a new skill, join a class, or dive into activities you enjoy.\n   - Spend time with friends and family who support and uplift you.\n\n### 5. **Reframe Your Perspective**\n   - Shift your focus from \u201cwhat could have been\u201d to what you can learn from the experience. Perhaps it taught you more about your desires, boundaries, or emotional resilience.\n   - View this as an opportunity to grow and prepare for a healthier connection in the future.\n\n### 6. **Practice Self-Compassion**\n   - Be kind to yourself during this process. Healing takes time, and it\u2019s okay to have moments of sadness or relapse.\n   - Avoid self-criticism or blaming yourself for how you feel.\n\n### 7. **Set New Goals**\n   - Create personal or professional goals to give yourself something to look forward to. This can help shift your focus away from the person and toward your own growth.\n\n### 8. **Consider Professional Support**\n   - If you\u2019re struggling to move on or if your feelings are overwhelming, consider talking to a therapist or counselor. They can provide tools and strategies to help you process your emotions.\n\n### 9. **Give It Time**\n   - Healing isn\u2019t linear, and it may take time to fully let go of your feelings. Be patient with yourself and trust that the intensity of your emotions will fade over time.\n\n### 10. **Open Yourself to New Possibilities**\n   - When you're ready, allow yourself to meet new people and explore new connections. This doesn\u2019t mean rushing into something new, but being open to the idea that there are other people out there who could be a better fit for you.\n\nRemember, it\u2019s natural to feel attached to someone you cared about deeply, even if the relationship wasn\u2019t mutual or realized. With time, self-care, and intentional effort, you\u2019ll be able to move forward and find peace.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
